T1  - Ceos On the Edge: Earnings Manipulation and Stock-Based Incentive Misalignment
AU  - Zhang, Xiaomeng
AU  - Bartol, Kathryn M.
AU  - Smith, Ken G.
AU  - Pfarrer, Michael D.
AU  - Khanin, Dmitry M.
Y1  - 2008/04/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2008.31767230
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2008.31767230
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 241
EP  - 258
VL  - 51
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Synthesizing agency theory and prospect theory, we examined the effects of stock-based incentives on CEO earnings manipulation behaviors. In analyses of data compiled from the public companies listed in Compustat's Executive Compensation Database and a U.S. General Accounting Office restatements database, we found that CEOs were more likely to manipulate firm earnings when they had more out-of-the-money options and lower stock ownership. Firm performance and CEO tenure interacted with out-of-the-money options and ownership to influence CEO earnings manipulation behaviors. Our findings inform agency-based views by providing evidence that, under certain conditions, stock-based managerial incentives lead to incentive misalignment.
AB  - Synthesizing agency theory and prospect theory, we examined the effects of stock-based incentives on CEO earnings manipulation behaviors. In analyses of data compiled from the public companies listed in Compustat's Executive Compensation Database and a U.S. General Accounting Office restatements database, we found that CEOs were more likely to manipulate firm earnings when they had more out-of-the-money options and lower stock ownership. Firm performance and CEO tenure interacted with out-of-the-money options and ownership to influence CEO earnings manipulation behaviors. Our findings inform agency-based views by providing evidence that, under certain conditions, stock-based managerial incentives lead to incentive misalignment.
